3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* showq 8
6/* SUMMARY
7/* list the Postfix mail queue
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* \fBshowq\fR [generic Postfix daemon options]
10/* DESCRIPTION
11/* The \fBshowq\fR(8) daemon reports the Postfix mail queue status.
12/* The output is meant to be formatted by the postqueue(1) command,
13/* as it emulates the Sendmail `mailq' command.
14/*
15/* The \fBshowq\fR(8) daemon can also be run in stand-alone mode
16/* by the superuser. This mode of operation is used to emulate
17/* the `mailq' command while the Postfix mail system is down.
18/* SECURITY
19/* .ad
20/* .fi
21/* The \fBshowq\fR(8) daemon can run in a chroot jail at fixed low
22/* privilege, and takes no input from the client. Its service port
23/* is accessible to local untrusted users, so the service can be
24/* susceptible to denial of service attacks.
25/* STANDARDS
26/* .ad
27/* .fi
28/* None. The \fBshowq\fR(8) daemon does not interact with the
29/* outside world.
30/* DIAGNOSTICS
31/* Problems and transactions are logged to \fBsyslogd\fR(8).
32/* CONFIGURATION PARAMETERS
33/* .ad
34/* .fi
35/* Changes to \fBmain.cf\fR are picked up automatically as \fBshowq\fR(8)
36/* processes run for only a limited amount of time. Use the command
37/* "\fBpostfix reload\fR" to speed up a change.
38/*
39/* The text below provides only a parameter summary. See
40/* \fBpostconf\fR(5) for more details including examples.
41/* .IP "\fBconfig_directory (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
42/* The default location of the Postfix main.cf and master.cf
43/* configuration files.
44/* .IP "\fBdaemon_timeout (18000s)\fR"
45/* How much time a Postfix daemon process may take to handle a
46/* request before it is terminated by a built-in watchdog timer.
47/* .IP "\fBduplicate_filter_limit (1000)\fR"
48/* The maximal number of addresses remembered by the address
49/* duplicate filter for \fBaliases\fR(5) or \fBvirtual\fR(5) alias expansion, or
50/* for \fBshowq\fR(8) queue displays.
51/* .IP "\fBempty_address_recipient (MAILER-DAEMON)\fR"
52/* The recipient of mail addressed to the null address.
53/* .IP "\fBipc_timeout (3600s)\fR"
54/* The time limit for sending or receiving information over an internal
55/* communication channel.
56/* .IP "\fBmax_idle (100s)\fR"
57/* The maximum amount of time that an idle Postfix daemon process waits
58/* for an incoming connection before terminating voluntarily.
59/* .IP "\fBmax_use (100)\fR"
60/* The maximal number of incoming connections that a Postfix daemon
61/* process will service before terminating voluntarily.
62/* .IP "\fBprocess_id (read-only)\fR"
63/* The process ID of a Postfix command or daemon process.
64/* .IP "\fBprocess_name (read-only)\fR"
65/* The process name of a Postfix command or daemon process.
66/* .IP "\fBqueue_directory (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
67/* The location of the Postfix top-level queue directory.
68/* .IP "\fBsyslog_facility (mail)\fR"
69/* The syslog facility of Postfix logging.
70/* .IP "\fBsyslog_name (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
71/* The mail system name that is prepended to the process name in syslog
72/* records, so that "smtpd" becomes, for example, "postfix/smtpd".
73/* .PP
74/* Available in Postfix version 2.9 and later:
75/* .IP "\fBenable_long_queue_ids (no)\fR"
76/* Enable long, non-repeating, queue IDs (queue file names).
77/* FILES
78/* /var/spool/postfix, queue directories
79/* SEE ALSO
80/* pickup(8), local mail pickup service
81/* cleanup(8), canonicalize and enqueue mail
82/* qmgr(8), queue manager
83/* postconf(5), configuration parameters
84/* master(8), process manager
85/* syslogd(8), system logging
86/* LICENSE
87/* .ad
88/* .fi
89/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
90/* AUTHOR(S)
91/* Wietse Venema
92/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
93/* P.O. Box 704
94/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
95/*
96/* Wietse Venema
97/* Google, Inc.
98/* 111 8th Avenue
99/* New York, NY 10011, USA
100/*--*/

146/* Application-specific. */

148int var_dup_filter_limit;
149char *var_empty_addr;
150
151static void showq_reasons(VSTREAM *, BOUNCE_LOG *, RCPT_BUF *, DSN_BUF *,
152 HTABLE *);
153
154#define STR(x) vstring_str(x)
155
156/* showq_report - report status of sender and recipients */
157
158static void showq_report(VSTREAM *client, char *queue, char *id,
159 VSTREAM *qfile, long size, time_t mtime)
160{
161 VSTRING *buf = vstring_alloc(100);
162 VSTRING *printable_quoted_addr = vstring_alloc(100);
163 int rec_type;
164 time_t arrival_time = 0;
165 char *start;
166 long msg_size = size;
167 BOUNCE_LOG *logfile;
168 HTABLE *dup_filter = 0;
169 RCPT_BUF *rcpt_buf = 0;
170 DSN_BUF *dsn_buf = 0;
171 int sender_seen = 0;
172 int msg_size_ok = 0;
173
174 /*
175 * Let the optimizer worry about eliminating duplicate code.
176 */
177#define SHOWQ_CLEANUP_AND_RETURN { \
178 if (sender_seen > 0) \
179 attr_print(client, ATTR_FLAG_NONE, ATTR_TYPE_END); \
180 vstring_free(buf); \
181 vstring_free(printable_quoted_addr); \
182 if (rcpt_buf) \
183 rcpb_free(rcpt_buf); \
184 if (dsn_buf) \
185 dsb_free(dsn_buf); \
186 if (dup_filter) \
187 htable_free(dup_filter, (void (*) (void *)) 0); \
188 }
189
190 /*
191 * XXX addresses in defer logfiles are in printable quoted form, while
192 * addresses in message envelope records are in raw unquoted form. This
193 * may change once we replace the present ad-hoc bounce/defer logfile
194 * format by one that is transparent for control etc. characters. See
195 * also: bounce/bounce_append_service.c.
196 *
197 * XXX With Postfix <= 2.0, "postsuper -r" results in obsolete size records
198 * from previous cleanup runs. Skip the obsolete size records.
199 */
200 while (!vstream_ferror(client) && (rec_type = rec_get(qfile, buf, 0)) > 0) {
201 start = vstring_str(buf);
202 if (msg_verbose)
203 msg_info("record %c %s", rec_type, printable(start, '?'));
204 switch (rec_type) {
205 case REC_TYPE_TIME:
206 /* TODO: parse seconds and microseconds. */
207 if (arrival_time == 0)
208 arrival_time = atol(start);
209 break;
210 case REC_TYPE_SIZE:
211 if (msg_size_ok == 0) {
212 msg_size_ok = (start[strspn(start, "0123456789 ")] == 0
213 && (msg_size = atol(start)) >= 0);
214 if (msg_size_ok == 0) {
215 msg_warn("%s: malformed size record: %.100s "
216 "-- using file size instead",
217 id, printable(start, '?'));
218 msg_size = size;
219 }
220 }
221 break;
222 case REC_TYPE_FROM:
223 if (*start == 0)
224 start = var_empty_addr;
225 quote_822_local(printable_quoted_addr, start);
226 printable(STR(printable_quoted_addr), '?');
227 if (sender_seen++ > 0) {
228 msg_warn("%s: duplicate sender address: %s "
229 "-- skipping remainder of this file",
230 id, STR(printable_quoted_addr));
231 SHOWQ_CLEANUP_AND_RETURN;
232 }
233 attr_print(client, ATTR_FLAG_MORE,
234 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_QUEUE, queue),
235 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_QUEUEID, id),
236 SEND_ATTR_LONG(MAIL_ATTR_TIME, arrival_time > 0 ?
237 arrival_time : mtime),
238 SEND_ATTR_LONG(MAIL_ATTR_SIZE, msg_size),
239 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_SENDER,
240 STR(printable_quoted_addr)),
241 ATTR_TYPE_END);
242 break;
243 case REC_TYPE_RCPT:
244 if (sender_seen == 0) {
245 msg_warn("%s: missing sender address: %s "
246 "-- skipping remainder of this file",
247 id, STR(printable_quoted_addr));
248 SHOWQ_CLEANUP_AND_RETURN;
249 }
250 if (*start == 0) /* can't happen? */
251 start = var_empty_addr;
252 quote_822_local(printable_quoted_addr, start);
253 printable(STR(printable_quoted_addr), '?');
254 if (dup_filter == 0
255 || htable_locate(dup_filter, STR(printable_quoted_addr)) == 0)
256 attr_print(client, ATTR_FLAG_MORE,
257 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_RECIP,
258 STR(printable_quoted_addr)),
259 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_WHY, ""),
260 ATTR_TYPE_END);
261 break;
262 case REC_TYPE_MESG:
263 if (msg_size_ok && vstream_fseek(qfile, msg_size, SEEK_CUR) < 0)
264 msg_fatal("seek file %s: %m", VSTREAM_PATH(qfile));
265 break;
266 case REC_TYPE_END:
267 break;
268 }
269
270 /*
271 * Before listing any recipients from the queue file, try to list
272 * recipients from the corresponding defer logfile with per-recipient
273 * descriptions why delivery was deferred.
274 *
275 * The defer logfile is not necessarily complete: delivery may be
276 * interrupted (postfix stop or reload) before all recipients have
277 * been tried.
278 *
279 * Therefore we keep a record of recipients found in the defer logfile,
280 * and try to avoid listing those recipients again when processing
281 * recipients from the queue file.
282 */
283 if (rec_type == REC_TYPE_FROM
284 && (logfile = bounce_log_open(MAIL_QUEUE_DEFER, id, O_RDONLY, 0)) != 0) {
285 if (dup_filter != 0)
286 msg_panic("showq_report: attempt to reuse duplicate filter");
287 dup_filter = htable_create(var_dup_filter_limit);
288 if (rcpt_buf == 0)
289 rcpt_buf = rcpb_create();
290 if (dsn_buf == 0)
291 dsn_buf = dsb_create();
292 showq_reasons(client, logfile, rcpt_buf, dsn_buf, dup_filter);
293 if (bounce_log_close(logfile))
294 msg_warn("close %s %s: %m", MAIL_QUEUE_DEFER, id);
295 }
296 }
297 SHOWQ_CLEANUP_AND_RETURN;
298}
299
300/* showq_reasons - show deferral reasons */
301
302static void showq_reasons(VSTREAM *client, BOUNCE_LOG *bp, RCPT_BUF *rcpt_buf,
303 DSN_BUF *dsn_buf, HTABLE *dup_filter)
304{
305 RECIPIENT *rcpt = &rcpt_buf->rcpt;
306 DSN *dsn = &dsn_buf->dsn;
307
308 while (bounce_log_read(bp, rcpt_buf, dsn_buf) != 0) {
309
310 /*
311 * Update the duplicate filter.
312 */
313 if (var_dup_filter_limit == 0
314 || dup_filter->used < var_dup_filter_limit)
315 if (htable_locate(dup_filter, rcpt->address) == 0)
316 htable_enter(dup_filter, rcpt->address, (void *) 0);
317
318 attr_print(client, ATTR_FLAG_MORE,
319 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_RECIP, rcpt->address),
320 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_WHY, dsn->reason),
321 ATTR_TYPE_END);
322 }
323}

326/* showq_service - service client */
327
328static void showq_service(VSTREAM *client, char *unused_service, char **argv)
329{
330 VSTREAM *qfile;
331 const char *path;
332 int status;
333 char *id;
334 struct stat st;
335 struct queue_info {
336 char *name; /* queue name */
337 char *(*scan_next) (SCAN_DIR *); /* flat or recursive */
338 };
339 struct queue_info *qp;
340
341 static struct queue_info queue_info[] = {
342 MAIL_QUEUE_MAILDROP, scan_dir_next,
343 MAIL_QUEUE_ACTIVE, mail_scan_dir_next,
344 MAIL_QUEUE_INCOMING, mail_scan_dir_next,
345 MAIL_QUEUE_DEFERRED, mail_scan_dir_next,
346 MAIL_QUEUE_HOLD, mail_scan_dir_next,
347 0,
348 };
349
350 /*
351 * Sanity check. This service takes no command-line arguments.
352 */
353 if (argv[0])
354 msg_fatal("unexpected command-line argument: %s", argv[0]);
355
356 /*
357 * Skip any files that have the wrong permissions. If we can't open an
358 * existing file, assume the system is out of resources or that it is
359 * mis-configured, and force backoff by raising a fatal error.
360 */
361 for (qp = queue_info; qp->name != 0; qp++) {
362 SCAN_DIR *scan = scan_dir_open(qp->name);
363 char *saved_id = 0;
364
365 while ((id = qp->scan_next(scan)) != 0) {
366
367 /*
368 * XXX I have seen showq loop on the same queue id. That would be
369 * an operating system bug, but who cares whose fault it is. Make
370 * sure this will never happen again.
371 */
372 if (saved_id) {
373 if (strcmp(saved_id, id) == 0) {
374 msg_warn("readdir loop on queue %s id %s", qp->name, id);
375 break;
376 }
377 myfree(saved_id);
378 }
379 saved_id = mystrdup(id);
380 status = mail_open_ok(qp->name, id, &st, &path);
381 if (status == MAIL_OPEN_YES) {
382 if ((qfile = mail_queue_open(qp->name, id, O_RDONLY, 0)) != 0) {
383 showq_report(client, qp->name, id, qfile, (long) st.st_size,
384 st.st_mtime);
385 if (vstream_fclose(qfile))
386 msg_warn("close file %s %s: %m", qp->name, id);
387 } else if (errno != ENOENT) {
388 msg_warn("open %s %s: %m", qp->name, id);
389 }
390 }
391 vstream_fflush(client);
392 }
393 if (saved_id)
394 myfree(saved_id);
395 scan_dir_close(scan);
396 }
397 attr_print(client, ATTR_FLAG_NONE, ATTR_TYPE_END);
398}

400MAIL_VERSION_STAMP_DECLARE;

402/* main - pass control to the single-threaded server skeleton */
403
404int main(int argc, char **argv)
405{
406 static const CONFIG_INT_TABLE int_table[] = {
407 VAR_DUP_FILTER_LIMIT, DEF_DUP_FILTER_LIMIT, &var_dup_filter_limit, 0, 0,
408 0,
409 };
410 CONFIG_STR_TABLE str_table[] = {
411 VAR_EMPTY_ADDR, DEF_EMPTY_ADDR, &var_empty_addr, 1, 0,
412 0,
413 };
414
415 /*
416 * Fingerprint executables and core dumps.
417 */
418 MAIL_VERSION_STAMP_ALLOCATE;
419
420 single_server_main(argc, argv, showq_service,
421 CA_MAIL_SERVER_INT_TABLE(int_table),
422 CA_MAIL_SERVER_STR_TABLE(str_table),
423 0);
424}
